Step 1: Preliminaries¶

Understanding the date range in question¶

For data with a temporal component, it is often useful to either do a temporal train/test split to marginalize for seasonality factors in a model, or to select a model type that can natively capture any temporal trends (e.g. an RNN.) Let's see if any of that is at play:

Thoughts on the train/test split¶

These loans were all originated in Q1 2018 with a fairly even split across Jan/Feb/March. Because this data comes from a relatively small snapshot in time, and because the target distribution seems fairly consistent across each month, I don't think a temporal split or temporally-aware model will be necessary. If there were significant differences between these distributions, we could try training on January's data, validating on February's, and testing on March's to make our model more resilient to temporal effects, but I don't think that will be necessary.

If we had information about the lender or borrower for each loan, I would create a train/test split that ensures the same lender and borrower does not appear in both training and testing sets (to prevent leakage,) but since we do not I'm going to assume these are all unique borrowers and lenders and do a simple random sample for the train/test split.

Thoughts on the problem & usable features¶

When conducting research for this problem, I came across this page which seems to give the exact formula LendingClub uses calculating their interest rates: https://www.lendingclub.com/foliofn/rateDetail.action

And indeed, if we transform sub-grade into its numeric equivalent and compare it with interest rate values, we can see that there is a >99% correlation between the two:

But where's the fun in that?

So for this modeling problem, I'm going to assume that we're trying to predict an interest rate given only

  1. A borrower's financials and personal information.
  2. The loan amount and term the borrower requested. (More on this shortly)

I'm ignoring certain "deal" features ('installment' (which could be used with the loan amount and term to recover the interest rate,) 'grade', and 'sub_grade') which could leak target information.

I am choosing to include 'loan_amount' and 'term,' because it seems from LendingClub's literature that a borrower sets these in advance of listing their desired loan. Granted, since they are used as modifiers to LendingClub's baseline grade to determine the final interest rate, they may leak some target information. However, they're also so critical in determining an interest rate I want to leave them in for now. At the end of the day the question is what will this model be used for? This work assumes we have the information of what kinds of loan amounts and terms people are looking for and we want to predict the interest rate they might be offered.

One caveat to this logic is that the 'initial_listing_status' feature does seem to indicate that a borrower can dispurse their loan among more than one lender, which perhaps indicates that these "loan amount" and "term" features may not be set in stone, and there may be some interplay between borrowers and lenders haggling over details, but I'm going to set that aside for now and just pretend that the loan amount and term are fixed and can be used in our feature set.

Other assumptions I'm making include:

  • The assumption that this is a "pre-origination" model, and as such, any "performace" features in the dataset (these include 'loan_status', 'initial_listing_status', 'disbursement_method', 'balance', 'paid_total', 'paid_principal', 'paid_interest', and 'paid_late_fees') will be ignored.

  • The assumption that the credit features present were pulled as of the loan application and not as of latest performance date.

  • The assumption that the interest rate is fixed and has not been adjusted since origination.

The last two seem like safe assumptions, but I could not find information in the data dictionary to confirm them.

With our problem now well defined, we can begin modeling!

Step 2: Data Cleaning, EDA, and Feature Engineering¶

Handling Columns with Null Values¶

In [8]:

How should each of these be handled?

  • emp_title: Given the context of this feature, I'm going to fill these as strings with the value "NULL." I may not have time to really dive into employment title as much as I might like, so I'm also going to create a dummy variable for missing employment titles, which may be the only feature I derive from this column.
  • emp_length: This is making an assumption, but if employment title is missing I'm going to assume the individual is unemployed (I was unable to find any listing of "unemployed" or variant thereof in the non-null values of emp_title, and there is a 98% match between null values of "emp_title" and "emp_length".) For these I will fill emp_length as 0, assuming that generally longer employment should be correlated with stability and therefore a potentially lower interest rate.
  • debt_to_income: because the percentage is so low, I'm going to drop these values. This does beg the question of how to handle missing DTI values if this model were to be deployed, which is a valid concern. If I have time perhaps I can explore some kind of imputation for these missing values.
  • annual_income_joint, verification_income_joint, debt_to_income_joint: These are tricky because they represent useful information that affects a significant enough segment of the population, but we can't have all of these null values in our model. If we had more credit information about the coborrowers, I would create two separate rows for the borrower and coborrower, and find some calibrated weight between the prediction for the borrower and coborrower that would maximize the model's acccuracy. Given that we only have little information, however, I'm going to treat joint applicants as a single individual and replace their Income, DTI, and Verification with their joint counterparts. There already exists a variable for indicating that indicates whether a loan was joint or not, so I'm not going to include another.
  • months_since_last_delinq, months_since_90d_late, months_since_last_credit_inquiry: I'm going to assume that these values all represent borrowers who have never had a delinquency, a 90d late, or a previous credit inquiry, and not that this information was simply unavailable (which is a big assumption.) I'm going to make another assumption and say that these features are all, at their core, proxies for recent credit behavior-- e.g., lower values of months_since_last_delinq should be a higher indicator for risk than high values. Because of this, I'm going to fill these values with the maximum of their respective column +1. Tree based models should be able to pick up on this split naturally, but other model types may have a hard time (e.g. linear regressions.) Therefore I will also add a dummy missingness variable for each.
  • num_accounts_120d_past_due: Because the null percentage is so low, and there is only one non-null unique value (0) for this column, I'm going to drop this feature.

Let's execute that logic:

# emp_title
modeling_df['emp_title_NULL'] = modeling_df['emp_title'].isnull().astype(int)
modeling_df['emp_title'] = modeling_df['emp_title'].apply(lambda x: 'NULL' if pd.isnull(x) else x)

# emp_length
modeling_df['emp_length'] = modeling_df['emp_length'].apply(lambda x: 0 if pd.isnull(x) else x)

# debt_to_income
modeling_df = modeling_df.dropna(subset='debt_to_income')

# annual_income_joint, verification_income_joint, debt_to_income_joint
def convert_income(x):
    if pd.isnull(x['annual_income_joint']):
        return x['annual_income']
    else:
        return x['annual_income_joint']

def convert_verification(x):
    if pd.isnull(x['verification_income_joint']):
        return x['verified_income']
    else:
        return x['verification_income_joint']
    
def convert_dti(x):
    if pd.isnull(x['debt_to_income_joint']):
        return x['debt_to_income']
    else:
        return x['debt_to_income_joint']

modeling_df['annual_income'] = modeling_df.apply(lambda x: convert_income(x), axis=1)
modeling_df['verified_income'] = modeling_df.apply(lambda x: convert_verification(x), axis=1)
modeling_df['debt_to_income'] = modeling_df.apply(lambda x: convert_dti(x), axis=1)

modeling_df = modeling_df.drop(['annual_income_joint', 'verification_income_joint', 'debt_to_income_joint'], axis=1)

# months_since_last_delinq, months_since_90d_late, months_since_last_credit_inquiry
modeling_df['months_since_last_delinq_NULL'] = modeling_df['months_since_last_delinq'].isnull().astype(int)
modeling_df['months_since_90d_late_NULL'] = modeling_df['months_since_90d_late'].isnull().astype(int)
modeling_df['months_since_last_credit_inquiry_NULL'] = modeling_df['months_since_last_credit_inquiry'].isnull().astype(int)

mmd = max(modeling_df['months_since_last_delinq']) + 1
m90d = max(modeling_df['months_since_90d_late']) + 1
mlc = max(modeling_df['months_since_last_credit_inquiry']) + 1

modeling_df['months_since_last_delinq'] = modeling_df['months_since_last_delinq'].apply(lambda x: 
                                                                                        mmd if pd.isnull(x) else x)
modeling_df['months_since_90d_late'] = modeling_df['months_since_90d_late'].apply(lambda x: 
                                                                                  m90d if pd.isnull(x) else x)
modeling_df['months_since_last_credit_inquiry'] = modeling_df['months_since_last_credit_inquiry'].apply(lambda x: 
                                                                                                        mlc if pd.isnull(x) else x)

# num_accounts_120d_past_due
modeling_df = modeling_df.drop('num_accounts_120d_past_due', axis=1)

Clipping & Transforming Numeric Outliers¶

I'm hesitant to clip outlier values automatically as much of this data is highly skewed, and relies on infrequent event (e.g. collections.) I'm going to first get a list of numeric and categorical columns, then I will calcullate columns with potential outliers (defined as >5 standard deviations from the mean,) and finally I will do a visual check to confirm which columns I want to clip outliers on and which I want to transform (in this case, log-scale.)

In [10]:
numeric_cols = [col for col in modeling_df.columns if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(modeling_df[col])]
In [11]:
cat_cols = list(set(modeling_df.columns) - set(numeric_cols))
In [12]:
outlier_cols = []
for col in numeric_cols:
    col_limit = np.mean(modeling_df[col]) + 5*np.std(modeling_df[col])
    num_outliers = sum(modeling_df[col]>col_limit)
    if num_outliers > 0:
        outlier_cols.append(col)
for col in outlier_cols:
    print(col)
    print('Max_value: {}'.format(max(modeling_df[col])))
    # creating a figure composed of two matplotlib.Axes objects (ax_box and ax_hist)
    f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.15, .85)})

    # assigning a graph to each ax
    sns.boxplot(x=modeling_df[col], ax=ax_box)
    sns.histplot(data=modeling_df, x=col, ax=ax_hist)

    # Remove x axis name for the boxplot
    ax_box.set(xlabel='')
    plt.show()

From these plots, the only values I'm very comfortable clipping are annual incomes. This is partially because they are self-reported, while other values come from credit pulls which tend to be more trustworthy, and partially because it's the only column with what seems like a ridiculous skew.

To clip, I will set the annual income as one more than the outlier limit I described above.

I will also create log-transformed versions of the following columns to make them easier to visualize:

  • annual_income
  • total_credit_limit
  • total_credit_utilized
  • total_debit_limit
In [13]:
inc_limit = np.mean(modeling_df['annual_income']) + 5*np.std(modeling_df['annual_income'])
modeling_df['annual_income'] = modeling_df['annual_income'].apply(lambda x: inc_limit + 1 if x > inc_limit else x)

# Adding 1 to avoid log(0) issues-- shouldn't change the distributions wildly
modeling_df['log_annual_income'] = np.log(modeling_df['annual_income']+1)
modeling_df['log_total_credit_limit'] = np.log(modeling_df['total_credit_limit']+1)
modeling_df['log_total_credit_utilized'] = np.log(modeling_df['total_credit_utilized']+1)
modeling_df['log_total_debit_limit'] = np.log(modeling_df['total_debit_limit']+1)

Encoding Categorical Features¶

If I had more time, I would dig into employment title more and try and create some kind of broader categorization for it which captures the "stability," "potential growth," etc. features which employment title may be a proxy for. As we already have a dummy variable for missing employment, I'm going to disregard this feature for now.

Similarly, State is an interesting feature because it can be a proxy for localized economic trends. If I was pulling in external data, matching someone's state to their local unemployment rate, housing price trends, etc. might be interesting. We can capture some of this information by creating ratios of, say, someone's income to their state average (creating an income feature which better normalizes for cost of living fluctuations,) but on it's own I will likely disregard State for now.

The other categorical features ('loan_purpose','application_type', 'homeownership', 'verified_income') I will one-hot encode. For loan purpose, I am bucketing some of the less-frequent values into an "other" category to control the feature space.

to_ohe = ['loan_purpose','application_type', 'homeownership', 'verified_income']

def encode_categoricals(data, categorical):
    enc = OneHotEncoder(drop='if_binary')
    for col in categorical:
        data[col] = data[col].astype(str)
    enc.fit(data[categorical])
    ohe_cols = enc.transform(data[categorical]).toarray()
    feature_names = enc.get_feature_names_out(input_features=categorical)
    ohe_dataset = pd.DataFrame(np.asarray(ohe_cols).reshape((data.shape[0], len(np.asarray(feature_names)))), 
                               columns=np.asarray(feature_names), 
                               index = data.index)
    non_ohe = list(set(data.columns)-set(categorical))
    data = data[non_ohe].merge(ohe_dataset, left_index=True, right_index=True)
    return data
modeling_df = encode_categoricals(modeling_df, to_ohe)

# Many models have trouble capturing "ratio" relationships between features,

# Also creating some "normalized" income and loan amount features that place them relative to state averages
# (choosing median for income and loan amount because they're both fairly skewed)
state_income_avgs = modeling_df.groupby('state')['annual_income'].median().to_dict()
state_loan_amount_avgs = modeling_df.groupby('state')['loan_amount'].median().to_dict()

modeling_df['ratio_income_to_state_avg'] = modeling_df.apply(lambda x: x['annual_income']/state_income_avgs[x['state']], axis=1)
modeling_df['ratio_loan_amt_to_state_avg'] = modeling_df.apply(lambda x: x['loan_amount']/state_loan_amount_avgs[x['state']], axis=1)

Step 4: Modeling¶

I'm going to create three different models: one ridge regression, one tree-based regressor, and one deep network regressor. I'll compare the results of each and unpack their scores.

  • First thing is to drop columns I created along the way for visualization, as well as other unusable columns (state, emp_title.)
  • Then I will create a train/test split, and some standardized feature sets for training the Linear Regression and Neural Network.
  • I will create each model, examine the train and test scores of each, and plot them with a regression line

In [32]:
def nn_model(num_columns, num_labels, hidden_units, dropout_rates, learning_rate):
    inp = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(num_columns, ))
    x = BatchNormalization()(inp)
    x = Dropout(dropout_rates[0])(x)
    for i in range(len(hidden_units)):
        x = Dense(hidden_units[i], activation='relu')(x)
        x = BatchNormalization()(x)
        x = Dropout(dropout_rates[i + 1])(x)
    x = Dense(num_labels)(x)
  
    model = Model(inputs=inp, outputs=x)
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate), 
                  loss='mean_absolute_error', 
                  metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.MeanSquaredError()]
                 )
    return model

num_columns = X_train_scaled.shape[1]
num_labels = 1
hidden_units = [16]
dropout_rates = [0.1, 0, 0.1, 0]
learning_rate = 1e-3

    num_columns=num_columns, 
    num_labels=num_labels,
    hidden_units=hidden_units,
    dropout_rates=dropout_rates,
    learning_rate=learning_rate
)

def R_squared(y, y_pred):
    residual = sum((y - y_pred)**2)
    total_ss = sum((y - np.mean(y))**2)
    r2 = 1-residual/total_ss
    return r2

print('Neural Net Train Score: {}'.format(R_squared(y_train, dn_preds_train.flatten())))
print('Neural Net Test Score: {}'.format(R_squared(y_test, dn_preds.flatten())))

print("Neural Net Test Score (RMSE): {}".format(dn_mse**(1/2.0)))

Step 5: Model Decomposition¶

One interesting thing I love to double click into is model decomposition. I unfortunately don't have the time for an exhaustive deep dive, but I wanted to give a flavor of what it can tell you about how you model treats your features.

Shown below are two kinds of explainability: SHAP values (applied to the ridge regression and XGB models) and Integrated Gradients (applied to the neurall network.) Each plot shows the top 20 most important features in the model; the color indicates how high or low the feature value is, and the position of each data point shows how it influences the model's score (right meaning a higher interest rate, left meaning a lower interest rate.)

For example, we can see below that the loan term is the most important feature in the ridge model. When its value is high it indicates a higher interest rate, and when its value is low it indicates a lower interest rate. We can see that toal debit limit is also an important feature, but its behavior is opposite: when the feature values are low, it's a semi-weak indicator towards a higher interest rate, but when the values are high it's a strong indicator towards a lower interest rate.

def tf_integrated_gradients(ob, base, model, n_steps):

    assert len(model.input.shape) == len(ob.shape), \
                                    "Model input and passed observation should have same length shape"
    def _parameterize(ob, base, n_steps):
        """
        See above docstring for arg defs
        """
        step = tf.math.divide(tf.math.subtract(ob, base), n_steps)
        path = []
        for i in range(n_steps):
            path.append(base+(step*i))
        return path, step

    if len(base.shape) != len(ob.shape):
        assert False, "reference should have the same shape as the observation. Try using np.expand_dims(reference, axis=0) if passing one reference point"
    
    num_refs = base.shape[0]
    all_exps = np.zeros(np.append(num_refs, ob.shape))
    for i in range(base.shape[0]):
        # create path from baseline to observation-- see _paramaterize helper function
        path, step = _parameterize(ob, base[i], n_steps)

        # Item assignment should be coming, look into it
        # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37697747/typeerror-tensor-object-does-not-support-item-assignment-in-tensorflow
        gradients = []

        # Calculate the gradient w.r.t. the input of the model's prediction for every point in the path
        for step_point in path:

            with tf.GradientTape() as tape:

                # Whatever we watch here, we can get the gradient w.r.t.
                tape.watch(step_point)

                # Get model prediction at our step point
                prediction = model(step_point)

            # Get the gradients of the prediction w.r.t to the input image, assign to gradients[step_i]
            # Also doing an extra step here where we multiply the gradient by the step-- need to for
            # the Riemann sum
            gradients.append(tape.gradient(prediction, step_point)*step)

        # Convert the list of tensors to a single tensor
        gradients = tf.convert_to_tensor(gradients)

        # Sum gradient*step across path
        explanation = tf.reduce_sum(gradients, axis=0)
        all_exps[i] = np.expand_dims(np.array(explanation), axis=0)

    avg_expl = np.mean(all_exps, axis=0)

    return np.array(explanation)
reference_ind = np.where(y_test==np.median(y_test))[0][:1]
ig_vals = tf_integrated_gradients(X_test_scaled.values, X_test_scaled.iloc[reference_ind].values, dn_mod, n_steps=200)

Conclusion¶

This was a fun challenge! As we can see, the modeling problem is a lot harder when we don't have access to the internal credit rating of LendingClub, but I was able to show a semi-strong correlation between my model's scores and the actual interest rates. Knowing that we're essentially trying to create a proxy model for LendingClub's grading system, I feel like it might be possible to do a lot better. I believe their scoring system is based on a combination of FICO and their internal credit model, and although we don't have access to FICO we do have a fair bit of bureau data to draw from.

If I had more time in this challenge, I would have done a lot more feature engineering, perhaps incorporating some automated feature creation and selection, I would have spent longer hypertuning my models, I would have tried some dimmensionality reduction techniques like PCA to better analyze and model the data, and I would have taken more advantage of the model explainability tools above to better unpack and retool my models.

If you read this far, thank you! This was one of the most fun assessments I've had this year.
